<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Group Life Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Makes all Event Points in the same colour and letter group come alive when mission logic triggers it.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Group Life Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Group Life</Bold> Event Point activates every Event Point that shares its
        <Bold>colour</Bold> and <Bold>letter group</Bold>. When it fires, all waypoints in that
        colour/group combination become alive, meaning they start processing their own triggers and
        behaviour.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is useful when a mission needs to enable a set of enemies, waypoints, or objectives at a
        specific moment rather than having them active from mission start. Group Life has no
        type-specific Data settings - the colour and group it targets come from the Event Point's
        standard common properties.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Set this Event Point's Colour and Group to match the set of Event Points you want to activate. When the Group Life fires, every waypoint with that exact colour+group becomes alive.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group Life uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point type,
        letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. <Bold>Colour</Bold> and
        <Bold>letter group</Bold> are the critical fields - they determine which Event Points this
        Group Life will activate. Position is usually not what matters for the activation itself, but
        can be used to keep the Group Life near its target set for organisation.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Colour
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Colour is one half of the targeting selector. A Group Life with <Bold>Purple</Bold> affects
        only Event Points that also use <Bold>Purple</Bold>. All other colours are ignored. The
        colour field is in the common Event Point properties section.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Group (Letter)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group letter is the other half of the selector. A Group Life with letter <Bold>A</Bold>
        affects only Event Points that also use letter <Bold>A</Bold>. The combination of
        <Bold>Colour + Group</Bold> is what defines the target set. Purple/A is different from
        Purple/B or Red/A.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Position does not affect which Event Points are activated. Group Life targets by
        colour+group, not by spatial radius. Use position only for placing the Event Point
        somewhere logical for mission authoring, such as near the trigger that causes it or near
        the center of the target group.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings control when the group comes alive. Most retail Group Life Event Points use
        <Bold>Dependency</Bold> so another Event Point explicitly activates the group. Some use
        <Bold>None</Bold> when the group should be active from mission start.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Listening Mode
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Group Life examples use <Bold>Active</Bold>. This is appropriate for a one-time
        group activation. Avoid persistent listening modes unless repeated activation is specifically
        intended and tested.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Group Life-Specific Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group Life has <Bold>no type-specific Data settings</Bold>. The Event Point's behaviour is
        entirely determined by the Colour and Group fields in the common properties section, plus
        the trigger that causes it to fire.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Create the enemies or waypoints first and set them to a common Colour+Group. Then create the Group Life and set it to the same Colour+Group. When the Group Life fires, the entire set activates.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Missions Trigger Group Life
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Group Life usage focuses on scripted enemy waves and objective activation. Useful
        trigger patterns are:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> - the most common pattern. The group comes alive after another Event Point fires, such as entering an area, completing an objective step, or triggering a conversation.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>None</Bold> - used when the group should be alive from mission start. This is less common than using Dependency, because most groups are enabled partway through the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Active</Bold> - the observed listening mode for Group Life entries. The activation happens once when the trigger fires.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run> Group Life affects every Event Point with the matching Colour+Group, not just enemies. Make sure the Colour+Group combination is used only by the Event Points you intend to activate.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Group Life Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Activate Enemy Wave After Player Action</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> when a set of enemies should come alive after the player
        triggers a specific Event Point, such as entering a zone, picking up an item, or completing
        a conversation.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Acarry.ucm</Bold>, Group Life <Bold>24</Bold> targets <Bold>Purple</Bold> group
        <Bold>A</Bold>. It uses <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>22</Bold> with
        listening mode <Bold>Active</Bold>. When Event Point <Bold>22</Bold> fires, every Event
        Point marked Purple/A becomes alive.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Set the enemy or objective Event Points to a specific Colour+Group, for example
        <Bold>Purple/A</Bold>. Add a <Bold>Group Life</Bold> Event Point with the same
        <Bold>Purple/A</Bold> combination, set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold>,
        and set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the Event Point that should cause the activation.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Pairing Group Death And Group Life</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Group Death</Bold> with <Bold>None/Active</Bold> at mission start to keep a set
        of Event Points dormant, then use <Bold>Group Life</Bold> with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> to
        bring them alive at the scripted moment.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Acarry.ucm</Bold>, Group Death <Bold>25</Bold> targets <Bold>Purple/A</Bold> and
        uses trigger <Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold>. It immediately makes all Purple/A
        Event Points dead when the mission starts. Later, Group Life <Bold>24</Bold> also targets
        <Bold>Purple/A</Bold> and uses <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>22</Bold>,
        bringing the group alive at the scripted moment.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Add a <Bold>Group Death</Bold> Event Point with the target Colour+Group and set trigger to
        <Bold>None</Bold> so it fires at mission start. Then add a <Bold>Group Life</Bold> Event
        Point with the same Colour+Group and use a <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger pointing at the
        Event Point that should activate the group.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Multiple Colour/Group Targets In One Mission</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use different Colour+Group combinations when a mission has several independent enemy waves
        or objective sets that should activate at different moments.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Bankbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Group Death <Bold>71</Bold> and Group Life <Bold>72</Bold>
        both target <Bold>Terracotta/O</Bold>, while Group Life <Bold>74</Bold> targets
        <Bold>Purple/A</Bold>. Each colour+group represents a separate set of Event Points that can
        be activated independently.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Assign each enemy wave or objective set to its own Colour+Group. Use a Group Life for each
        distinct combination. This keeps each set's activation logic independent and prevents
        accidental cross-activation.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Group At Mission Start</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use trigger <Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold> when the group should be alive from
        the very beginning of the mission instead of waiting for a scripted trigger.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Bankbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Group Life <Bold>72</Bold> targets
        <Bold>Terracotta/O</Bold> and uses trigger <Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold>. All
        Terracotta/O Event Points are alive as soon as the mission loads.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Set the Group Life's trigger to <Bold>None</Bold> and listening mode to <Bold>Active</Bold>.
        This is simpler than leaving Event Points alive by default, because it lets you explicitly
        control which groups start alive versus dead.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Group Life Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create or identify the Event Points that should be activated together as a group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set all of those Event Points to the same <Bold>Colour</Bold> and <Bold>Group</Bold> letter combination.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Group Life</Bold> Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the Group Life's <Bold>Colour</Bold> and <Bold>Group</Bold> to match the target set.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For scripted activation, set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the Event Point that should activate the group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For mission-start activation, set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>None</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use listening mode <Bold>Active</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the group should start dead, add a <Bold>Group Death</Bold> Event Point with the same Colour+Group and trigger <Bold>None/Active</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test the mission and confirm the group activates only at the intended moment and that the correct Event Points are affected.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Verify that no unintended Event Points share the same Colour+Group, which would cause them to activate along with the intended group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> The Group Life's Colour+Group matches the target Event Points exactly, the trigger fires only at the correct mission moment, and no unintended Event Points share that Colour+Group combination.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
